{
  "texts": [
    "The map Em:P d (Q) → L ∞ (Q), given by Em([ i (f i, π i)]) = i f i det Dπ i is called the canonical embedding (for potential forms).The definition of Em is valid due to Lemma 3.6 which asserts that the choice of the representative is irrelevant.",
    "Since we do not know whether weak equivalence is equivalent to equivalence, we are not able to assert that Em is injective.",
    "We shall nevertheless call it an \"embedding\".From now on, we will use the shorthand notationT (f, π) = T (f, π 1,..., π d) for (f, π 1,..., π d) ∈ Lip b × [Lip] d.Definition 3.8.",
    "Given a current T ∈ D d (Q) and a potential form ω ∈ P d (Q), we define their duality pairing as ⟨ω,T ⟩ = i T (f i, π i), where i (f i, π i) ∈ ω.Once again, by definition of ∼, the choice of the representative is irrelevant.Theorem 3.9.",
    "The space P d is complete.Proof."
  ]
}